              </li>
                      </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
    <section class="banner-carousel-card grid_wrapper grid_wrapper--large">
      <div class="heading-container">
                <h3>
          Living with tigers
        </h3>
              </div>
      <div class="splide">
        <div class="splide__track">
          <ul class="splide__list">
                                                                                                <li class="splide__slide" data-link-url="" data-link-text="Find out more">
                <figure>
                  <div class="caption-link-bg">
                    <figcaption>
                                                                                          <h4>Pilibhit Tiger Reserve</h4>
                                            <p>Pilibhit Tiger Reserve in the foothills of the Himalayas is a long, narrow reserve flanked by densely populated areas. Tiger numbers have more than doubled in the reserve over the last decade, but with blurred borders between tiger habitat and human settlements, the area became a hotspot for human tiger conflict.&nbsp;&nbsp; Atul Singh knows the landscape and its tigers intimately. His grandfather was a famous tiger hunter and he had grown up with great respect for tigers. Atul became increasingly concerned about conflict between communities and tigers. “People suffered many losses,” he explains. “Because of that, some people decided to kill the tigers themselves.” Atul decided to put his tracking skills he learnt from his grandfather to use, to lead the way in helping people and tigers coexist. With the help of WWF, Atul has built a team of 12 tiger trackers from the towns and villages surrounding Pilibhit. They now work with the Forest Department to locate tigers, monitor their movements, spread awareness in their communities on how to stay safe and, in extreme circumstances, relocate them. The team goes by the name of the Bagh Mitra, or ‘Tiger Friends.’ Today there are some 200 Bagh Mitra in communities surrounding Pilibhit Tiger Reserve.</p>
                    </figcaption>
                                      </div>
                </figure>
              </li>
                                                                                                <li class="splide__slide" data-link-url="" data-link-text="Find out more">
                <figure>
                  <div class="caption-link-bg">
                    <figcaption>
                                                                                          <h4>The Sundarbans</h4>
                                            <p>The Sundarbans area of West Bengal is made up of 104 low-lying islands where tigers prowl the mangrove forests. The forest provides protection against storms and rising sea levels and is a crucial source of food and income for many of the 4.5 million people who live in the area. It is also home to around 100 tigers and tragic tales of human-tiger encounters are not difficult to come by. Mahua Pramanik comes from a long line of moulis - traditional wild honey collectors – and used to travel into the forest with her family to make a living. These days, an alternative way of making money means she no longer needs to risk her life but can continue with her family’s traditional practice. Mahua and her husband are one of around 80 families involved in a honey cooperative that uses apiaries placed in secure, netted areas on the edge of the forest. “It’s much safer to do it this way, and the bees still collect pollen from the mangrove trees so the honey retains its high quality” she says. Mahua says that while it might seem like life would be easier without tigers there is a growing awareness that tigers are essential for the preservation of the ecosystem on which the people of the Sundarbans depend.&nbsp; “If tigers weren’t there, people would destroy the forest by cutting down all its trees to earn a living” she says. “The environmental balance would be destroyed and we would face even worse damage from the storms.”&nbsp;</p>
                    </figcaption>
                                      </div>
                </figure>
              </li>
                      </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="cta-pagination-container">
          <div class="splide-arrows-bg">
