                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1200/public/2022-08/Potential%20future%20only%201080x1080.png?h=57024e64&amp;itok=N0bBxIlq 1200w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1440/public/2022-08/Potential%20future%20only%201080x1080.png?h=57024e64&amp;itok=px8n7eq8 1440w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1536/public/2022-08/Potential%20future%20only%201080x1080.png?h=57024e64&amp;itok=_y9GmPLV 1536w"
                       alt="Restoring Asia&#039;s Roar"
                       sizes="(max-width:768px) 95vw, 25vw"
                  />
                                      <div class="splide-copyright">© WWF-UK</div>
                                    <figcaption>
                    <h4>RESTORING ASIA’S ROAR</h4>
                    <div class="figure-text-container">
                      <p><p>A new WWF report outlines incredible opportunities for boosting nature recovery by expanding wild tigers’ range. While current tiger range has shrunk by around 95% over the past hundred years, there is potential to more than double its current size. Many of these recovery areas serve as critical carbon sinks. Protecting these important landscapes for tiger recovery would not only help contribute to global climate change mitigation goals but would also generate significant top-down ecological benefits to people, wildlife and the planet. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p></p>
                    </div>
                  </figcaption>
                                                          <div class="find-out-more-container">
                                                              <a href="https://www.wwf.org.uk/learn/wildlife/tigers" class="find-out-more-btn">
                        READ THE REPORT
                      </a>
                                      </div>
                                  </figure>
              </li>
                      </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="splide__arrows splide__arrows--ltr">
          <button
            class="splide__arrow splide__arrow--prev"
            type="button"
            aria-label="Previous slide"
            aria-controls="splide01-track"
          >
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 40 40" width="40" height="40" focusable="false">
              <path d="m15.5 0.932-4.3 4.38 14.5 14.6-14.5 14.5 4.3 4.4 14.6-14.6 4.4-4.3-4.4-4.4-14.6-14.6z"></path>
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="text-link-pagination">
            <p><span class="text-link-current"></span>/<span class="text-link-total"></span></p>
          </div>
          <button
            class="splide__arrow splide__arrow--next"
